'''Velvet Revolver''' is an American [[hard rock]] [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]] consisting of former [[Guns N' Roses]] members [[Slash (musician)|Slash]], [[Duff McKagan]] and [[Matt Sorum]], alongside [[Dave Kushner]], formerly of [[Hardcore punk|punk]] band [[Wasted Youth (American band)|Wasted Youth]]. [[Stone Temple Pilots]] vocalist [[Scott Weiland]] was Velvet Revolver's lead singer from their formation until 2008. In 2004, the band achieved commercial success with their debut album, ''[[Contraband (Velvet Revolver album)|Contraband]]''. Despite positive reviews, some critics initially described Velvet Revolver as a mere combination of Stone Temple Pilots and Guns N' Roses, criticizing them for a "disconnection" between Scott Weiland and the rest of the band. With their single "[[Slither (song)|Slither]]", they won the 2005 [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]].

The band released ''[[Libertad (Velvet Revolver album)|Libertad]]'' in 2007, driven by the release of the single "[[She Builds Quick Machines]]", and embarked on a tour with [[Alice in Chains]]. In April 2008, Weiland left Velvet Revolver and [[2008 Stone Temple Pilots Reunion Tour|reunited with Stone Temple Pilots]]. Velvet Revolver has been on indefinite hiatus since April 2008, and in November of that year, the band was released by their record label [[RCA Records]] at their request to allow them "complete freedom to go through whatever process it would take to accomplish" replacing Weiland.

The release of Slash's [[Slash (album)|self-titled debut solo album]] and Duff McKagan's addition to the [[Jane's Addiction]] lineup seemed to put the future of the band in doubt. However, McKagan left Jane's Addiction a few months after joining. Despite being on hiatus, Velvet Revolver has written new songs and plans to audition singers and reconvene in 2011.

==History==
===Formation (1996<U+2013>2003)===
[[Image:SaulHudson.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Guitarist [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] performing at a concert in [[Nijmegen]]. Slash formed Velvet Revolver with [[Duff McKagan]], [[Matt Sorum]], [[Dave Kushner]], and [[Scott Weiland]].]]
Slash, Duff McKagan, and Matt Sorum were members of hard rock band [[Guns N' Roses]]. Slash and McKagan had been members since 1985, while Sorum joined the band in 1990.<ref name="Guns N' Roses AMG">{{Cite web | author = [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine|Thomas Erlewine, Stephen]] | coauthor = Prato, Greg | title = Guns N' Roses Biography | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = November 14, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4416/biography|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> Guns N' Roses toured and achieved international success following the release of the albums ''[[Appetite for Destruction]]'', ''[[Use Your Illusion I]]'', and ''[[Use Your Illusion II]]''. However, a distancing relationship with singer [[Axl Rose]] resulted in Slash, in 1996, and McKagan, in 1997, leaving the band while Sorum was fired the same year.<ref name="Guns N' Roses AMG"/> Following their departures, the trio focused on separate projects with Slash reforming [[Slash's Snakepit]]<ref name="Slash AMG">{{Cite web | last = Huey | first = Steve | title = Slash Biography | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = November 14, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=slash-p125919/biography|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> and McKagan reforming [[10 Minute Warning]],<ref name="Duff McKagan AMG">{{Cite web | last = Torreano | first = Bradley | title = Duff McKagan Biography | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = November 14, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p104254/biography|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref><ref name="10 Minute Warning AMG">{{Cite web | last = Ankeny | first = Jason | title = 10 Minute Warning Biography | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = November 14, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p294177/biography|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> as well as recording his second solo album<ref name="Duff McKagan AMG"/> while Sorum rejoined [[The Cult]].<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 397 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref>

Despite being involved with other projects, the trio occasionally collaborated. Slash guested on McKagan's unreleased second solo album ''Beautiful Disease'',<ref name="Beautiful Disease AMG">{{Cite web | last = W. Valdivia | first = Victor | title = Beautiful Disease Review | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = November 14, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=beautiful-disease-r430925/review|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> while the trio recorded original music for the independent film ''Soundman''<ref name="Slamdance">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Slamdance Film Fest To Feature Perry Farrell, Former Guns N' Roses Members, Sheryl Crow And Others | publisher = [[MTV]] | date = December 29, 1998 | url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1427656/19981229/crow_sheryl.jhtml}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Soundman (1998) | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate = April 9, 2010 | url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0134974/}}</ref> in 1998. They also performed together with [[Lanny Cordola]], [[Chuck Wright]], and [[Teddy Andreadis]] for a one-hour plus concert at the [[Slamdance Film Festival]] in [[Park City, Utah]] to promote the film in 1999.<ref name="Slamdance"/> Rumors quickly arose of a Guns N' Roses reunion, however, McKagan stated that they "[were] just [t]here to play. It's not that big of a deal, but [they] play good together."<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Guns N' Roses Alums Say Show No Big Deal | publisher = [[MTV]] | date = January 28, 1999 | url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429790/19990128/guns_n_roses.jhtml}}</ref>

By 2001, Slash's Snakepit had disbanded for the second time.<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 410 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> Slash began working with [[The Black Crowes]] drummer [[Steve Gorman]] and an unnamed bassist on a new project:<ref name="VR Ultimate Guitar">{{Cite web | last = Rosen | first = Steven | title = Velvet Revolver: 'We're Straight Up F--kin? Rock'. Part 2 | publisher = [[Ultimate Guitar Archive]] | date = February 11, 2006 | url = http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/velvet_revolver_were_straight_up_f--kin_rock_part_2.html}}</ref> writing the music for what would become "Fall to Pieces".<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 415 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> McKagan reformed [[Loaded (band)|Loaded]],<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Duff McKagan releases "Dark Days" as LOADED | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = June 20, 2001 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=150}}</ref> previously his band for the tour in support of ''Beautiful Disease'',<ref name="Hard Force Magazine">{{Cite web | last = Oliveira | first = Daniel | title = Duff McKagan Interview | work = Hard Force Magazine | date = June 1999 | url = http://www.heretodaygonetohell.com/articles/showarticle.php?articleid=26}}</ref> with [[Geoff Reading]]. McKagan also added both [[Mike Squires (musician)|Mike Squires]] and [[Jeff Rouse (musician)|Jeff Rouse]] to the lineup.<ref name="Sputnikmusic Interview">{{Cite web | last = de Sylvia | first = Dave | title = Duff McKagan's Loaded Interview | publisher = [[Sputnikmusic]] | date = September 29, 2008 | url = http://www.sputnikmusic.com/feature.php?id=5403}}</ref> Following a tour of Japan in 2002,<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Former GUNS N' ROSES Bassist Announces West Coast, Japanese Dates | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = January 12, 2002 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=748}}</ref> former [[Zilch (band)|Zilch]], [[Wasted Youth (American band)|Wasted Youth]], [[Electric Love Hogs]], and [[Dave Navarro]] guitarist [[Dave Kushner]] joined Loaded in place of Mike Squires.<ref name="Dave Kushner KNAC">{{Cite web | last = Stingley | first = Mick | title = Exclusive! Interview With Velvet Revolver Guitarist Dave Kushner | publisher = [[KNAC]] | date = July 14, 2004 | url = http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=3136}}</ref>

When musician [[Randy Castillo]] died from cancer in 2002, Slash, McKagan, and Sorum performed at a benefit concert to raise money and commemorate Castillo<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 423 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> with [[Josh Todd]] and Keith Nelson of [[Buckcherry]] as well as [[B-Real]] and [[Sen Dog]] of [[Cypress Hill]].<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 424 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> Recognizing that their musical relationship was still intact,<ref name="AMG Bio">{{Cite web | last = Loftus | first = Johnny | title = Velvet Revolver Biography | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = July 20, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p651389/biography|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> the trio began rehearsing with Todd<ref name="AMG Bio"/> and Nelson, working on material that would become "Dirty Little Thing",<ref name="Contraband booklet">{{Cite album-notes | title = Contraband | albumlink = Contraband (Velvet Revolver album) | bandname = Velvet Revolver | year= 2004 | publisher = [[RCA Records]] | format = CD booklet}}</ref> but eventually decided against forming a group with them.<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 425 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref><ref name="Slash p.426">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 426 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> During a Loaded show at Hollywood's [[Viper Room]],<ref name="Slash p.426"/> McKagan introduced Kushner to Slash, who were previously friends in junior high and high school.<ref name="Dave Kushner KNAC"/><ref name="Slash p.427">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 427 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> Kushner was invited to jam with the group and was soon invited to join with Slash, stating that "Dave brought a cool vibe to what [they] were doing. There was no deliberation; that was it, it was a perfect fit."<ref name="Slash p.427"/> Their former Guns N' Roses band mate [[Izzy Stradlin]] also joined them for two weeks,<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 428 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> eventually suggesting that "Duff and [Stradlin] will sing and [they] will just do a club tour in a van." Slash states in his autobiography that it was hard to tell if Stradlin was serious or kidding.<ref name="Slash p.429">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 429 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> After auditioning Kelly Shaefer of [[Atheist (band)|Atheist]] and [[Neurotica (band)|Neurotica]],<ref name="AMG Bio"/> Stradlin left the group.<ref name="Slash p.429"/>

While Shaefer's audition was unsuccessful, the quartet continued auditioning for a lead singer, with [[VH1]] filming the recruitment process<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 431 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> while being referred to as the temporary name "The Project".<ref name="AMG Bio"/> The resulting documentary was aired as VH1 Inside Out: The Rise of Velvet Revolver. A number of lead singers auditioned for the band, including [[Todd Kerns]], formerly of [[Age of Electric]],<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Canada's TODD KERNS Among Candidates For Singer Slot In Ex-GNR Project | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = December 31, 2002 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=8550}}</ref><ref name="Kerns/Albro">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Canadian Singer Confirms Audition With Ex-GUNS N' ROSES Members | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = January 4, 2003 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=8641}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Canadian Singer TODD KERNS Misses The VELVET REVOLVER Boat | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = September 8, 2004 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=26629}}</ref> [[Sebastian Bach]], formerly of [[Skid Row (American band)|Skid Row]],<ref name="Slash p.432">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 432 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> Shawn Albro of [[U.P.O.]],<ref name="Kerns/Albro"/> and [[Travis Meeks]] of [[Days of the New]].<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = DAYS OF THE NEW Frontman Collaborates With Former GUNS N' ROSES Members | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = December 9, 2002 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=8101}}</ref> [[Myles Kennedy]], formerly of [[The Mayfield Four]], declined an invitation from Sorum to audition.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SLASH, MYLES KENNEDY Interviewed In London | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = June 25, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=142121}}</ref> [[Ian Astbury]] of [[The Cult]] and [[Mike Patton]] of [[Faith No More]]<ref name="Classic Rock Contraband"/> also declined audition offers.<ref name="Classic Rock Contraband">{{Cite book | last = Milas | first = Alexander | title = Classic Rock presents Slash: Forbidden Fruit | work = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | year = 2010 | page = 123 | isbn = 1-858703-18-2 }}</ref> The band were also interested in auditioning [[Stone Temple Pilots]] singer [[Scott Weiland]], who had become friends with McKagan after attending the same gym.<ref name="Weiland Washington Post">{{Cite web | last = Freedom du Lac | first = J | title = Velvet Revolver, A Legal Substance | work = [[The Washington Post]] | date = August 2007 | url = http://blog.washingtonpost.com/virgin-festival/2007/08/post_1.html}}</ref><ref name="Weiland Details">{{Cite web | last = Hendrickson | first = Matt | title = Scott Weiland Sobers Up . . . Again | work = [[Details (magazine)|Details]] | date = April 2010 | url = http://www.details.com/celebrities-entertainment/music-and-books/201004/scott-weiland-stone-temple-pilots-singer?currentPage=2}}</ref> Weiland once played on the same bill as Kushner,<ref name="Slash p.432"/> and was in rehab at the same time as Sorum.<ref name="Slash p.432"/><ref name="Weiland Details"/> Weiland was sent two discs of material,<ref name="Weiland Washington Post"/> and felt that the first disc "sounded like [[Bad Company]] gone wrong."<ref name="Weiland Washington Post"/> When he was sent the second disc, Weiland was more positive, comparing it to ''[[Core (album)|Core]]''-era Stone Temple Pilots,<ref name="Weiland Washington Post"/> though he turned them down because Stone Temple Pilots were still together.<ref name="Slash p.432"/>

{{Quote box|width=28%|align=right|quote="I just thought he was a great singer, and he'd always been on my mind for this band. He was the one vocalist that I knew had the kind of voice that would serve what we were going to do: he had a [[John Lennon]]-ish quality, a little bit of [[Jim Morrison]], and a touch of almost [[David Bowie]]. He was the best singer to come out in a long time in my opinion."<ref name="Slash p.432"/> |source=<U+2014>Slash on Scott Weiland}}
When Stone Temple Pilots disbanded in 2003,<ref name="Slash p.433">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 433 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> the band sent Weiland new music, which he took into his studio and added vocals. This music eventually becoming the song "Set Me Free".<ref name="Dave Kushner KNAC"/><ref name="Slash p.433"/> Despite delivering the music to the band himself, Weiland was still unsure whether or not he wanted to join them,<ref name="Slash p.433"/> despite performing at an industry showcase at Mates.<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 434 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> They recorded two songs with producer [[Nick Raskulinecz]],<ref name="Slash p.436">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 436 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> a recorded version of "[[Set Me Free (Velvet Revolver song)|Set Me Free]]" and a cover of [[Pink Floyd]]'s "[[Money (Pink Floyd song)|Money]]", for the soundtracks to the movies ''[[Hulk (film)|The Hulk]]'' and ''[[The Italian Job (2003 film)|The Italian Job]]'', respectively.<ref name="Slash p.436"/> Weiland joined the band soon after.<ref name="Weiland Washington Post"/> "Set Me Free" managed to peak at number 17 on the [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Mainstream Rock Chart]]<ref name="AMG Singles">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Velvet Revolver Singles Charts | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = July 20, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=velvet-revolver-p651389/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> without any radio promotion or a record label.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Steele | first = Laurie | title = Exclusive! Interview With Velvet Revolver Drummer Matt Sorum | publisher = [[KNAC]] | date = July 26, 2004 | url = http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=3152}}</ref> It was prior to a screening of ''The Hulk'' at [[Universal Studios]] that the band chose a name.<ref name="Slash p.437">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 437 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> After seeing a movie by [[Revolution Studios]],<ref name="Slash p.437"/> Slash liked the beginning of the word, eventually thinking of Revolver because of its multiple meanings; the name of a gun, subtext of a revolving door which suited the band as well as the name of a [[Revolver (album)|Beatles album]].<ref name="Slash p.437"/> When he suggested Revolver to the band, Weiland suggested back Black Velvet Revolver, liking the idea of "something intimate like velvet juxtaposed with something deadly like a gun."<ref name="Slash p.437"/> They eventually arrived at Velvet Revolver,<ref name="Slash p.437"/> announcing it at a press conference and performance showcase at the [[El Rey Theatre]]<ref name="Slash p.437"/> while also performing the songs "Set Me Free" and "Slither" as well as covers of [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s "Negative Creep", [[Sex Pistols]]' "[[Pretty Vacant]]", and Guns N' Roses' "[[It's So Easy]]".<ref name="Slash p.437"/>

===''Contraband'' and mainstream success (2003<U+2013>2005)===
{{listen |filename=Slither.ogg |title=Slither |description=A sample of "[[Slither (song)|Slither]]" from ''[[Contraband (Velvet Revolver album)|Contraband]]''. The band's debut single managed to top both the [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Mainstream]] and [[Hot Modern Rock Tracks|Modern Rock Chart]]. It is considered the band's signature song and is frequently the closer to their shows. |filename2=Fall to Pieces.ogg |title2=Fall to Pieces |description2=A sample of "[[Fall to Pieces (Velvet Revolver song)|Fall to Pieces]]" from ''[[Contraband (Velvet Revolver album)|Contraband]]''. The second single released by Velvet Revolver managed to top the Mainstream Rock Chart. |format=[[Ogg]]}}
Prior to the recording of their debut album, Weiland took material that the band had previously written to his studio, Lavish, in [[Toluca Lake, Los Angeles|Toluca Lake]].<ref name="Slash p.438">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 438 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> With engineer [[Doug Grean]], Weiland rearranged the music to fit his vocals, eventually coming out with the songs "Big Machine" and "Dirty Little Thing".<ref name="Slash p.438"/> The band worked on new material for songs such as "You Got No Right", "Slither", "Sucker Train Blues", and "Do It for the Kids", among others.<ref name="Slash p.438"/> It was during this time that Weiland was arrested at the parking lot of his studio for [[drug possession]].<ref name="Slash p.438"/> Upon release from jail, he wrote lyrics to material he was given previously, writing the song "Fall to Pieces".<ref name="Slash p.438"/> Velvet Revolver soon began recording their debut album. Initially, they recorded "Slither" with producer [[Bob Ezrin]] at Henson Studios, but were dissatisfied with the result.<ref name="Slash p.439">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 439 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> After recording "Headspace" with [[Josh Abraham]], the band liked the track enough to do the rest of the album with him.<ref name="VR Ultimate Guitar"/><ref name="Slash p.439"/>

Velvet Revolver soon gained major label attention with [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] and [[Chrysalis Records|Chrysalis]]. [[RCA Records|RCA]] and [[Elektra Records|Elektra]] were also interested in signing the band.<ref name="Slash p.439"/> They eventually signed with RCA Records.<ref name="AMG Bio"/><ref name="Slash p.439"/> They recorded their album at [[NRG Recording Studios]], while Slash recorded his guitar parts at a smaller studio on the southern corner between [[Highland Avenue]] and [[Sunset Boulevard]].<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 440 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> During recording, Weiland could only work for three hours a day due to a court order mentioning that he was to stay in a [[halfway house]].<ref>{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 441 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> The marketing campaign for Velvet Revolver in the run-up to the release of the first album was profiled as part of the ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]'' program ''The Way the Music Died'',<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = The Way the Music Died: Artists' Stories | work = [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]] | accessdate = June 25, 2010 | url = http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/music/artists/}}</ref> which included interviews with the band members and producers.

The resulting album, titled ''[[Contraband (Velvet Revolver album)|Contraband]]'', was released on June 8, 2004,<ref name="Contraband Review">{{Cite web | last = Loftus | first = Johnny | title = Contraband Review | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = July 20, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=contraband-r691400/review|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> and, helped by the success of the single "[[Slither (song)|Slither]]",<ref name="AMG Bio"/> debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200]],<ref name="AMG Albums">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Velvet Revolver Album Charts | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = July 20, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=velvet-revolver-p651389/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> selling over 250,000 copies in the first week.<ref name="Classic Rock Contraband"/> ''Contraband'' went on to sell four million copies worldwide, 2.9 million of which were sold in the United States, and was certified 2x platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref name="Classic Rock Contraband"/><ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Gold and Platinum Database Search | publisher = [[Recording Industry Association of America]] | accessdate = June 25, 2010 | url = http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=Contraband&artist=Velvet%20Revolver&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2009&sort=Artist&perPage=25}}</ref> Both "Slither"<ref name="AMG Singles"/> and "[[Fall to Pieces (Velvet Revolver song)|Fall to Pieces]]"<ref name="AMG Singles"/> managed to peak at number one on the Mainstream Rock Chart as well as number 56 and 67 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]], respectively.<ref name="AMG Singles"/> "Slither" also peaked at number one on the [[Hot Modern Rock Tracks|Modern Rock Chart]] and number 35 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = UK Singles Chart info | publisher = Chartstats.com | accessdate = June 2, 2009 | url = http://www.chartstats.com/songinfo.php?id=251}}</ref> The album's third single, "[[Dirty Little Thing]]", peaked at number eight on the Mainstream Rock chart.<ref name="AMG Singles"/>

[[Image:Velvet Revolver, Download Festival 2005.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Velvet Revolver performing at [[Download Festival#Download 2005|Download Festival]] in 2005.]]
Critically, the album was generally well-received.<ref name="metacritic">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Critic Reviews for Contraband | publisher = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = November 17, 2010 | url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/contraband/critic-reviews}}</ref> Despite being praised for its hedonism and maturity,<ref name="Contraband AMG">{{Cite web | last = Loftus | first = Johnny | title = Contraband Review | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = July 20, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=contraband-r691400/review|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> critics noted a disconnection between "singer and band".<ref name="ShakingThrough">{{Cite web | last = Forest Moreau | first = Kevin | title = Velvet Landmines | publisher = ShakingThrough.net | date = June 16, 2004 | url = http://www.shakingthrough.net/music/reviews/2004/velvet_revolver_contraband_2004.html}}</ref><ref name="Contraband ew">{{Cite web | author = [[David Browne|Browne, David]] | title = Contraband Review | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | date = June 4, 2004 | url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,643204,00.html}}</ref> Velvet Revolver won the [[Kerrang! Awards#2004 Results|Kerrang! Award]] for Best International Newcomer in 2004, and the following year they won the [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]] Grammy Award for "Slither". They also received a nomination for Rock Artist of the Year at the [[Billboard Music Award]]s while "Fall to Pieces" was nominated for a Song of the Year/Rock Radio [[Radio Music Awards|Radio Music Award]]. They recorded a new song entitled "[[Come On, Come In]]" for the movie ''[[Fantastic Four (film)|Fantastic Four]]'' in 2005, which peaked at number 14 on the Mainstream Rock Chart.<ref name="AMG Singles"/> "Fall to Pieces" then re-entered the charts, peaking at number twenty-five on the [[Adult Top 40]] the same year.<ref name="AMG Singles"/>

Velvet Revolver toured extensively for nineteen months<ref name="Slash p.442">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 442 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> in support of ''Contraband''. They toured both the United States and Europe twice, while also performing in Australia, New Zealand, and Japan. They performed at [[Live 8]]<ref name="Slash p.442"/> and various festivals including [[Download Festival]]<ref name="Slash p.442"/> and [[Ozzfest]]. It was during the tour that the band members, with the exception of Kushner,<ref name="Weiland Split Spinner">{{Cite web | last = Dekel | first = Jonathan | title = Slash Sets the Record Straight on Velvet Revolver Split | publisher = [[Spinner (website)|Spinner]] | date = May 19, 2010 | url = http://www.spinnermusic.co.uk/2010/05/19/slash-velvet-revolver-split/}}</ref> began to relapse on alcohol and drugs.<ref name="Weiland Split Spinner"/><ref name="Duff CRR">{{Cite web | last = Wright | first = Jeb | title = Sick Things <U+2014> An Exclusive Interview with Duff McKagan | publisher = Classic Rock Revisited | date = May 19, 2010 | url = http://www.classicrockrevisited.com/interviewduffmckagan.htm}}</ref> Though they managed to get clean in time for the recording of their new album,<ref name="Weiland Split Spinner"/> Slash felt that "[the band] lost [Weiland]" and "thought the overall spirit of everything was declining at that point."<ref name="Weiland Split Spinner"/>

===''Libertad'' and hiatus (2005<U+2013>2008)===
{{listen |filename=She Builds Quick Machines.ogg |title=She Builds Quick Machines |description=A sample of "[[She Builds Quick Machines]]" from ''[[Libertad (Velvet Revolver album)|Libertad]]''. The band's first single from ''Libertad'' represents a change in music style compared to previous singles. |format=[[Ogg]]}}
Weiland announced in 2005 that Velvet Revolver's next album would be titled ''[[Libertad (Velvet Revolver album)|Libertad]]'' and would be a concept album.<ref name="Santa Barbara Independent">{{Cite web | last = Michaels | first = Levi | title = Velvet Revolver Drummer Matt Sorum Checks In from the Road | work = [[Santa Barbara Independent]] | date = September 6, 2007 | url = http://www.independent.com/news/2007/sep/06/velvet-revolver-drummer-matt-sorum-checks-road/}}</ref> When they started writing material, they decided against the concept idea.<ref name="Santa Barbara Independent"/> Initially, the band started working with producer [[Rick Rubin]] on the album. However, due to his methods, such as having a crew to do the work and engineering while only popping in occasionally,<ref name="Slash p.452">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 452 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> and due to the fact that he was also working with other bands at the same time,<ref name="Slash p.453"/> they decided against continuing with Rubin.<ref name="Slash p.452"/> At the suggestion of Weiland,<ref name="Slash p.452"/> Velvet Revolver began working with [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]].<ref name="Slash p.452"/> Slash stated that O' Brien "brought more than just discipline to the equation, he brought a musicality that stems from the fact that he plays guitar. bass and drums. At any given moment he could play along [the band] and it really helped the process."<ref name="Slash p.452"/> He also said that the "sessions were consistent, everyone was there, everyone contributed, and everyone appreciated what each player was doing" and that the "mutual participation surpassed the first Guns sessions."<ref name="Slash p.453">{{Cite book | author = Slash | coauthors = [[Anthony Bozza|Bozza, Anthony]] | title = [[Slash (autobiography)|Slash]] | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 2007 | page = 453 | isbn = 978-0 00-725775-1 }}</ref> While writing for the album, Weiland believed that his band mates were going to reunite with Guns N' Roses<ref name="Weiland GNR reunion">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SCOTT WEILAND 'Would Pay' To See GUNS N' ROSES Reunion | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = April 27, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=95790}}</ref> when the band's manager was talking to Axl Rose about switching management companies,<ref name="Weiland GNR reunion"/> and were not going to record their second album.<ref name="Weiland GNR reunion"/> He was later convinced by the band that this was not the case.<ref name="Weiland GNR reunion"/>

Following the completion of the album, Velvet Revolver performed for and inducted [[Van Halen]] into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]], with Weiland and Slash speaking on the band's behalf, on March 12, 2007.<ref name="Van Halen induction">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER To Perform For And Induct VAN HALEN Into ROCK HALL | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = March 1, 2007  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=68010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VAN HALEN Inducted Into ROCK AND ROLL HALL OF FAME; Photos, Video Available | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = March 9, 2007 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=68652}}</ref> The band played a medley of "[[Ain't Talkin' 'bout Love]]" and "Runaround".<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER To Perform ROTH And HAGAR Tunes At ROCK HALL | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = March 9, 2007 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=68495}}</ref> Shows in South American with [[Aerosmith]] followed in April.<ref name="Van Halen induction"/> They released the EP ''[[Melody and the Tyranny]]'' on June 1<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER: 'Melody And The Tyranny' EP Artwork, Track Listing Revealed | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = May 14, 2007 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=72471}}</ref> to serve as a precursor to the release of their new album, which featured two songs from ''Libertad'', a cover of [[Talking Heads]] song "[[Psycho Killer]]" and a video documentary about the making of ''Libertad'' as well as a live video of the band performing "Do It for the Kids".<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Bassist Comments On 'Melody And The Tyranny' EP | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = May 16, 2007 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=72662}}</ref>

[[Image:Velvet Revolver (3).JPG|right|thumb|180px|Bassist Duff McKagan performing at [[Gods of Metal]] in 2007.]]
''Libertad'' was released on July 3, 2007,<ref name="AMG Bio"/><ref name="Libertad AMG review">{{Cite web | author = [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine|Thomas Erlewine, Stephen]] | title = Libertad Review | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = July 20, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=libertad-r1059225/review|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> peaking at number five on the Billboard 200.<ref name="AMG Albums"/> The album's first single "[[She Builds Quick Machines]]" peaked at 74 on the [[Billboard charts#Canadian charts|Hot Canadian Digital Singles]].<ref name="AMG Singles"/> The second and third singles, "[[The Last Fight]]" and "[[Get Out the Door]]", both peaked at number 16 and 34 on the Mainstream Rock Chart, respectively.<ref name="Libertad AMG Singles">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Libertad Singles Charts | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = July 20, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=libertad-r1059225/charts-awards/billboard-single|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> Critical reception to the album was mixed. Though some critics praised the album<ref name="Libertad ew review">{{Cite web | last = Sinclair | first = Tom | title = Libertad (2007) | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | date = June 22, 2007 | url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20043357,00.html}}</ref><ref name="Libertad NYP review">{{Cite web | last = Aquilante | first = Dan | title = Velvet Revolver "Libertad" | work = [[New York Post]] | date = July 1, 2007 | url = http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/music/item_0uXzv8F1WQtAKHS0rPu0JL;jsessionid=EAFB5857EEF093FF3AF1A596B41A84CB}}</ref> and felt that ''Libertad'' gave the band an identity of their own,<ref name="Libertad SFC review">{{Cite web | last = Uhelszki | first = Jaan | title = Liberted Review | work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date = July 1, 2007 | url = http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/07/01/PKGT1P40MN1.DTL&type=music}}</ref> outside of the Guns N' Roses and Stone Temple Pilots comparisons, others described the album as "bland"<ref name="Libertad TAC review">{{Cite web | last = Hernandez | first = Raoul | title = Phases & Stages | work = [[The Austin Chronicle]] | date = July 20, 2007 | url = http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/issue/review?oid=oid%3A505117}}</ref><ref name="Libertad Blabbermouth review">{{Cite web | last = Kaye | first = Don | title = Velvet Revolver Libertad (RCA) | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = July 20, 2007 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=1173}}</ref> and noted that the band have still to gel with them "play[ing] to their strengths instead of finding a collective sound."<ref name="Libertad AMG review"/>

In support of ''Libertad'', Velvet Revolver toured North America and Canada with [[Alice in Chains]] from August 2007 to October.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Harris | first = Chris | title = Velvet Revolver Team With Alice In Chains For Summer Tour | publisher = [[MTV]] | date = May 22, 2007 | url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1560256/20070522/velvet_revolver.jhtml}}</ref> They also performed at the [[Virgin Festival]],<ref name="Weiland Washington Post"/> [[Gods of Metal]], and [[Download Festival#Download 2007|Download]] in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Members Denied Japanese Visas; Tour Cancelled | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = July 4, 2007 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=76052}}</ref> A November tour of Japan was canceled after they were denied visas,<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER, ALICE IN CHAINS: More North American Tour Dates Announced | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = November 14, 2007 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=84958}}</ref> and in 2008, a tour of Australia was postponed, due to health issues,<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Velvet Revolver delay tour | work = [[The Courier-Mail]] | date = November 29, 2007 | url = http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/velvet-revolver-delay-tour/story-e6freq7x-1111115003231}}</ref> and later canceled<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Cancels Australian Tour | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = February 10, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=90268}}</ref> following Weiland's decision to voluntarily enter a rehab facility.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER's SCOTT WEILAND Back In Rehab | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = February 7, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=90268}}</ref> On November 21, 2007, Weiland was arrested after crashing his car while driving on an L.A. highway. He was charged with driving under the influence of drugs with a prior conviction and later released on $40,000 bail.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Velvet Revolving Door -- Weiland Arrested Again | publisher = [[TMZ.com]] | date = December 3, 2007 | url = http://www.tmz.com/2007/12/03/velvet-revolving-door-weiland-arrested-again/?ewrd=1}}</ref> Velvet Revolver then toured both the US and the UK, as well as some European shows, on the [[Rock n' Roll as It Should Be]] tour from January 24 to April 1, 2008. They also played at the Dubai Desert Rock Festival on March 8 the same year.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = DUBAI DESERT ROCK FESTIVAL 2008: The Recap | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = March 13, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=92901}}</ref> It was during the tour that Weiland "got back into his old ways",<ref name="Loaded Bullz-Eye">{{Cite web | last = Harris | first = Will | title = A chat with Duff McKagan | publisher = Bullz-Eye | date = April 23, 2003 | url = http://www.bullz-eye.com/music/interviews/2009/duff_mckagan.htm}}</ref> which started to take their toll on the rest of the band<ref name="Duff CRR"/> with the cancellation of the Australian tour seen as the "final blow".<ref name="Weiland Split Spinner"/><ref name="UK Tour">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SLASH On Last Tour With SCOTT WEILAND: 'We Gave Him The Cold Shoulder Like Nobody's Business' | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = April 16, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=95057}}</ref> 

[[Image:Scott Weiland 2.jpg|left|thumb|180px|Former singer Scott Weiland. Velvet Revolver's April 1 show at the [[Heineken Music Hall]] in the [[Netherlands]] was the band's last performance with Weiland.]]
On the UK tour, the band members never spoke with Weiland, with the exception of a few arguments around the stage.<ref name="UK Tour"/> Tensions came to a head during Velvet Revolver's Glasgow show on March 20, 2008, where Weiland announced to the crowd that it was the band's last tour,<ref name="Glasgow show">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SCOTT WEILAND: This Is VELVET REVOLVER's 'Last Tour' | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = March 21, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=93384}}</ref> unaware that the band were already planning on firing him.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Slash Exclusive! The Truth About Weiland | work = [[Guitar World]] | date = Apr 18, 2008 | url = http://www.guitarworld.com/article/slash_exclusive_the_truth_about_weiland}}</ref><ref name="UK Tour"/> After Sorum posted a message about the show on his website,<ref name="Glasgow show"/> Weiland issued a statement through [[Blabbermouth.net]] in response, saying he "made many attempts to remain cordial with the members of [Velvet Revolver], but mainly, the likes of [Sorum]" and that "[the band] were a gang. But ego and jealousy can get the better of anyone."<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SCOTT WEILAND Fires Back At MATT SORUM: 'Ego And Jealousy Can Get The Better Of Anyone' | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = March 21, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=93414}}</ref> Slash later stated that it would not be Velvet Revolver's last tour.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SLASH: 'This Is Not VELVET REVOLVER's Last Tour' | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = March 25, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BLABBERMOUTH.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=93566}}</ref> Weiland's departure was announced on April 1.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = It's Official: VELVET REVOLVER Parts Ways With Singer SCOTT WEILAND | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = April 1, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=94021}}</ref> Weiland also departed the cover band [[Camp Freddy]],<ref name="Scott Weiland AMG">{{Cite web | last = Ankeny | first = Jason | title = Scott Weiland Biography | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = November 14, 2010 | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=scott-weiland-p136847/biography|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> which also featured Sorum, and has since [[2008 Stone Temple Pilots Reunion Tour|reunited with Stone Temple Pilots]].<ref name="Weiland Split Spinner"/><ref name="Scott Weiland AMG"/>

[[Image:Matt Sorum (457434291).jpg|right|thumb|180px|Drummer Matt Sorum. Sorum has been with the band since 2002.]]
Velvet Revolver soon began recording new material<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Lays Down '12 New Jams,' According To Bassist MCKAGAN | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = April 10, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=94640}}</ref> before going on hiatus, while a number of singers were rumoured to be working with the band. Amongst them were [[Lenny Kravitz]],<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = LENNY KRAVITZ Rumored To Be Rehearsing With VELVET REVOLVER | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = August 12, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102628}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = LENNY KRAVITZ: I Am Not Joining VELVET REVOLVER | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = August 12, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102665}}</ref> [[Chester Bennington]] of [[Linkin Park]],<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = LINKIN PARK's BENNINGTON: I Am Not VELVET REVOLVER's New Singer  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = June 16, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=99093}}</ref> Steve Isaacs formerly of [[Skycycle]] and [[The Panic Channel]],<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = THE PANIC CHANNEL Frontman: 'I Am Not Singing For VELVET REVOLVER' | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = June 24, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=99644}}</ref> Royston Langdon of [[Spacehog]],<ref>{{Cite web | last = Halperin | first = Shirley | title = Spacehog's Royston Langdon in the running for Velvet Revolver frontman | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | date = July 30, 2008 | url = http://insidetv.ew.com/2008/07/30/royston-langdon/}}</ref> [[Donovan Leitch (actor)|Donovan Leitch]] of Camp Freddy,<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Interview: Duff McKagan's Loaded | publisher = [[Nottingham Post]] | accessdate = June 18, 2008 | url = http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/news/Interview-Duff-McKagan-s-Loadeds/article-296193-detail/article.html}}</ref> and [[Scars on Broadway]] guitarist [[Franky Perez]],<ref name="Franky Perez">{{Cite web | last = Halperin | first = Shirley | title = Scott Weiland is like George Bush to me <U+2013> I like him now that he<U+2019>s gone<U+2026> | work = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = July 16, 2009 | url = http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/%e2%80%9cscott-weiland-is-like-george-bush-to-me-%e2%80%93-i-like-him-now-that-he%e2%80%99s-gone%e2%80%a6%e2%80%9d/}}</ref> as well as previous auditonee Sebastion Bach.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Sebastian Bach speaks about possibly joining Velvet Revolver | publisher = [[MusicRadar]] | date = May 8, 2008 | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/sebastian-bach-speaks-about-possibly-joining-velvet-revolver-153315}}</ref> [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] and [[Stone Sour]] singer [[Corey Taylor]] unsuccessfully auditioned for the band,<ref>[http://www.rockonaltitude.com/?p=2780 The future of SLIPKNOT in doubt? Corey spills the dirt on his new band] Revolver. Retrieved 2010-04-22</ref> while Velvet Revolver invited both Myles Kennedy<ref name="Myles Kennedy">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SLASH Says MYLES KENNEDY 'Turned Down' VELVET REVOLVER Singer Gig | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = July 27, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=143635}}</ref> and [[Shooter Jennings]]<ref name="Shooter Jennings">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Shooter Jennings Offered Velvet Revolver Job Twice! | work = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = March 19, 2009 | url = http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/shooter-jennings-offered-velvet-revolver-job-twice/}}</ref> to join. However, with Kennedy still in [[Alter Bridge]]<ref name="Myles Kennedy"/> and Jennings recording a new album,<ref name="Shooter Jennings"/> both turned the offer down. The band also approached their record label in June 2008, asking to be released from their recording contract<ref>{{Cite web | last = Bosso | first = Joe | title = Slash confirms Velvet Revolver's split from RCA Records | publisher = [[MusicRadar]] | date = November 26, 2008 | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/slash-confirms-velvet-revolvers-split-from-rca-records-184475}}</ref> to allow them "complete freedom to go through whatever process it would take to accomplish" replacing Weiland.<ref name="roadrunnerrecords.com">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Dropped by RCA/SONY BMG | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = November 14, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=108917}}</ref> Sony BMG/RCA dropped the band from the label in November of the same year.<ref name="roadrunnerrecords.com"/>

===Hiatus activities (2008<U+2013>2010)===
McKagan reunited with previous band Loaded in 2008,<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = DUFF MCKAGAN's LOADED To Enter Studio This Month | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = April 1, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=94000}}</ref> releasing an EP entitled ''[[Wasted Heart]]'' the same year McKagan also released the band's second album, entitled ''[[Sick (Loaded album)|Sick]]'', in 2009.<ref name="Duff McKagan Ultimate Guitar">{{Cite web | last = Rosen | first = Steven | title = Duff McKagan: 'I'm Influenced By Everything I've Heard' | publisher = [[Ultimate Guitar Archive]] | date = April 23, 2009 | url = http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/duff_mckagan_im_influenced_by_everything_ive_heard.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = DUFF MCKAGAN'S LOADED: 'Sick' First-Week Sales Revealed | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = April 17, 2009 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=118300}}</ref> They completed the recording of their third album with producer [[Terry Date]] in 2010,<ref name="Terry Date SW">{{Cite web | last = McKagan | first = Duff | title = One Loaded Summer | work = [[Seattle Weekly]] | date = September 2, 2010 | url = http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/reverb/2010/09/one_loaded_summer.php}}</ref> and began collaborating with [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]] and [[Documentary film|documentarian]] Jamie Burton Chamberlin on a film based on the album the same year.<ref name="Loaded film">{{Cite web | last = Shay | first = Steve | title = Seattle rock legend Duff McKagan & West Seattle filmmaker collaborate | work = [[West Seattle Herald]] | date = October 31, 2010 | url = http://www.westseattleherald.com/2010/10/31/news/seattle-rock-legend-duff-mckagan-west-seattle-fil}}</ref> McKagan joined [[Jane's Addiction]] in March 2010, replacing founding bassist [[Eric Avery]].<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Jane's Addiction 'Writing and Creating' With Bassist Duff McKagan | publisher = [[Spinner (website)|Spinner]] | date = March 30, 2010 | url = http://www.spinnermusic.co.uk/2010/03/30/janes-addiction-with-bassist-duff-mckagan/}}</ref> However, his tenure with the band lasted only five months, with his departure from the band announced on September 6 of the same year.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Goodman | first = Dean | title = Ex-Guns N' Roses bassist leaves Jane's Addiction | publisher = [[Reuters]] | date = September 6, 2010 | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE6852OR20100906}}</ref>

[[Image:Velvet Revolver (5).JPG|right|thumb|180px|Second guitarist [[Dave Kushner]]. During the band's hiatus, Kushner composed music for television and films.]]
Kushner began composing music for film and television. He co-wrote the theme song entitled "[[This Life (Theme from Sons of Anarchy)|This Life]]" for [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] series [[Sons of Anarchy]],<ref name="Monsters and Critics">{{Cite web | last = Luce | first = Patrick | title = Velvet Revolver<U+2019>s Dave Kushner co-writes <U+2018>Sons of Anarchy<U+2019> theme song | publisher = [[Monsters and Critics]] | date = September 5, 2008 | url = http://www.monstersandcritics.com/music/news/article_1429058.php/Velvet_Revolver_s_Dave_Kushner_co-writes_Sons_of_Anarchy_theme_song}}</ref> receiving an [[Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music|Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]] in 2009<ref name="The Film Music Society">{{Cite web | last = Burlingame | first = Jon | title = Emmy Music Nominations Announced | publisher = [[The Film Music Society]] | date = July 16, 2009 | url = http://www.filmmusicsociety.org/news_events/features/2009/071609.html?isArchive=071609}}</ref> and an [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers#Annual Awards|ASCAP Award]] in 2010.<ref name="Variety ASCAP">{{Cite news | last =  Morris | first =  Christopher | title = ASCAP Honors Top Film and Television Music Composers at 25th Anniversary Awards Celebration | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date = June 24, 2010 | url = http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118021027.html?categoryid=16&cs=1}}</ref> In 2010, he and John O'Brien composed the music for the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] drama series [[Detroit 1-8-7]].<ref name="Dave Kushner IMDb">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Dave Kushner | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate = July 12, 2010 | url = http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1396919}}</ref><ref name="Detroit 187 IMDb">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = "Detroit 187" (2010) | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate = July 12, 2010 | url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1578258/combined}}</ref> He also contributed music to the films ''[[Four Christmases]]'' and ''[[Couples Retreat]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Guitarist DAVE KUSHNER Receives 2009 EMMY Nomination | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = September 18, 2009 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=125478}}</ref> Kushner also collaborated with Scars on Broadway guitarist Franky Perez,<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = 10 Things You Didn<U+2019>t Know About Franky Perez | work = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = July, 2009 | url = http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-franky-perez/}}</ref> who had previously worked with Velvet Revolver,<ref name="Franky Perez"/> releasing songs under the pseudonym of [[DKFXP]]. One of the songs, "Beyond the Wire", was later used in the film ''[[Hisss]]'', with the new title of "Beyond the Snake". The song featured vocals and lyrics by [[Shruti Haasan]].<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Hisss-toric soundtrack for Mallika! | work = [[The Times of India]] | date = September 26, 2010 | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Hisss-toric-soundtrack-for-Mallika/articleshow/6629944.cms}}</ref> In 2010, Kushner and [[Dave Navarro]] collaborated on a cover of [[The Kinks]]' "[[You Really Got Me]]" to be used in a [[Hyundai Motor Company|Hyundai]] commercial.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = JANE'S ADDICTION, VELVET REVOLVER Guitarists Record 'You Really Got Me' Cover For HYUNDAI | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = September 21, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=146397}}</ref>

Sorum continued work on cover band Camp Freddy's debut album<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = CAMP FREDDY Continuing Work On Debut Album | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = May 17, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BlabberMouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=97212}}</ref> before guesting on [[Sammy Hagar]]'s solo album ''[[Cosmic Universal Fashion]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Drummer MATT SORUM To Guest On SAMMY HAGAR's New Album | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = July 15, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BlabberMouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=100932}}</ref> He also produced two songs, entitled "Are You Blind" and "Coming For You", for Los Angeles-based band, Drive A, in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = MATT SORUM Produces Songs For DRIVE A | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = September 10, 2008 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BlabberMouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=104475}}</ref> In 2010, Sorum formed the cover band Carnival of Dogs with Franky Perez, [[L.A. Guns]] guitarist [[Tracii Guns]], and former [[Ozzy Osbourne]] and [[Billy Idol]] bassist [[Phil Soussan]]<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER, L.A. GUNS, SCARS ON BROADWAY Members Join Forces In CARNIVAL OF DOGS | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = May 22, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BlabberMouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=140530}}</ref> before going on to tour with [[Mot<U+00F6>rhead]], temporarily filling in for drummer [[Mikkey Dee]].<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Sorum: <U+2018>I<U+2019>ve Got 25 Blisters Drumming For Mot<U+00F6>rhead<U+2019> | work = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = September 29, 2010 | url = http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/matt-sorum-ive-got-25-blisters-drumming-for-motorhead/}}</ref> He also began working with [[Cherie Currie]], formerly of [[The Runaways]], on her new solo album.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = MATT SORUM Working On CHERIE CURRIE's Comeback Album | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = November 10, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BlabberMouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=149147}}</ref>

Slash worked on his solo album, writing and demoing songs before sending them to numerous singers and musicians.<ref name="Classic Slash">{{Cite book | last = Wall | first = Mick | title = Classic Rock presents Slash: What Friends Are For | work = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | year = 2010 | page = 11 | isbn = 1-858703-18-2 }}</ref> Recorded with producer [[Eric Valentine]],<ref name="Classic Slash"/> ''[[Slash (album)|Slash]]'', released on March 31, 2010, featured a number of guests such as [[Andrew Stockdale]] of [[Wolfmother]], [[M. Shadows]] of [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Kid Rock]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Myles Kennedy]], and [[Fergie]], among others.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Slash album track by track | publisher = [[MusicRadar]] | date = March 4, 2010 | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/slash-solo-album-interview-the-track-by-track-guide-238767#content}}</ref> His band for the tour in support of the album consisted of Myles Kennedy, guitarist Bobby Schneck, and drummer [[Brent Fitz]]. It also included early Velvet Revolver audtionee Todd Kerns on bass.<ref>{{Cite news | last =  Bosso | first =  Joe | title = Interview: Myles Kennedy talks Alter Bridge, Slash and Led Zeppelin | publisher = [[MusicRadar]] | date = November 30, 2010 | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/interview-myles-kennedy-talks-alter-bridge-slash-and-led-zeppelin-314959}}</ref> He also guested on [[Rihanna]]'s album ''[[Rated R (Rihanna album)|Rated R]]'' on the song "[[Rockstar 101]]",<ref>{{Cite news | last =  | first =  | title = Rihanna Confirms Slash, Will.i.am, Young Jeezy Guest on "Rated R" | publisher = [[Artistdirect]] | date = November 2, 2009 | url = http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/rihanna-confirms-slash-will-i-am-young-jeezy-guest-on-rated-r/0axO7VJ2eg5U3}}</ref> as well as Kennedy's debut solo album while also confirming that his next solo album would feature Kennedy as the sole vocalist.<ref name="Rock AAA">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Slash signs up Kennedy for second solo album | publisher = Rock AAA | date = November 22, 2010 | url = http://www.rockaaa.com/news/slash-signs-up-kennedy-for-second-solo-album-885#}}</ref><ref name="Kennedy MusicRadar">{{Cite news | last = Bosso | first = Joe | title = Interview: Myles Kennedy talks Alter Bridge, Slash and Led Zeppelin. Part 2 | publisher = [[MusicRadar]] | date = November 30, 2010 | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/interview-myles-kennedy-talks-alter-bridge-slash-and-led-zeppelin-314959/2}}</ref>

===Possible return (2010<U+2013>present)===
After running into one another on a flight to Las Vegas in February 2010, Slash stated he had "no issues" with Weiland and that he was excited to hear the [[Stone Temple Pilots (album)|new Stone Temple Pilots album]],<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SLASH Runs Into SCOTT WEILAND On Way To Las Vegas | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = February 22, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=135564}}</ref> and also stated that, in May, unlike the "Guns N' Roses situation", he and Weiland are still friends.<ref name="Weiland Split Spinner"/> Weiland also later stated that his time with the band was a "great experience until near the end" and that he "[does not] hold any resentment towards any of the guys in the band."<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = SCOTT WEILAND At Peace With VELVET REVOLVER | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = May 14, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BlabberMouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=140037}}</ref> Velvet Revolver soon began writing new songs and auditioning new singers,<ref name="Blabbermouth.net">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Trying Out Two Singers Next Month | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = September 25, 2010  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=146660}}</ref><ref name="London Free Press">{{Cite web | last = Stevenson | first = Jane | title = Slash cuts loose: Rock's guitar hero steps out on his own with star-studded CD | work = [[London Free Press]] | date = April 2, 2010 | url = http://www.lfpress.com/entertainment/music/2010/03/31/13426126.html}}</ref><ref name="Seattle Weekly">{{Cite web | last = Kornelis | first = Chris | title = Duff McKagan Addresses the Jane's Addiction Rumors, the Velvet Revolver Talk, and Those Missed Deadlines | work = [[Seattle Weekly]] | date = April 7 2010 | url = http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/reverb/2010/04/duff_mckagan_confronts_the_jan.php}}</ref> with Slash stating that "the new material is a lot heavier than what Velvet Revolver has put out, so [he is] dying to put out the quintessential Velvet Revolver record."<ref name="consequenceofsound">{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = Velvet Revolver to reunite for new album without Scott Weiland? | work = Consequence of Sound | date = June 4, 2010 | url = http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/06/04/velevet-revolver-to-reunite-for-new-album-without-scott-weiland/}}</ref> Rumours quickly arose that Myles Kennedy was to be the new Velvet Revolver vocalist<ref name="Slash CRR">{{Cite web | last = Wright | first = Jeb | title = Slash: Dangerously Beautiful | publisher = Classic Rock Revisited | date = May 19, 2010 | url = http://www.classicrockrevisited.com/interviewSlash.htm}}</ref> due to his collaborations with Slash. However, Slash confirmed that no effort was made to have Kennedy join the band.<ref name="Slash CRR"/> Kennedy also stated that while joining "Velvet Revolver [would] be enticing, [he made plans] and [his] plate is pretty full."<ref name="Kennedy MusicRadar"/>

Slash, McKagan, and Sorum all contributed to the song "[[Kissed It]]" for the [[Macy Gray]] album ''[[The Sellout]]'', which was released on June 22.<ref name="VR Macy Gray">{{Cite news | last =  | first =  | title = Former GUNS N' ROSES Members Featured On New MACY GRAY Album | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = May 21, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BlabberMouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=140502}}</ref> Despite not featuring Kushner, the trio were credited as Velvet Revolver on the album.<ref name="VR Macy Gray"/> The band released their first concert DVD on November 16, entitled ''Live In Houston'', which was filmed in 2005 while the band was touring in support of ''Contraband''.<ref>{{Cite web | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER: 'Live In Houston' DVD Due Next Month | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = October 14, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=147703}}</ref> The same month, Slash revealed that a "big name" singer is due to audition soon for Velvet Revolver,<ref name="Rock AAA"/> with more auditions also being held in December.<ref>{{Cite news | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Auditioning More Singers This Week | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = December 6, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=150480}}</ref> Sorum revealed in December that the band were close to finding a new singer. They agreed on one person, describing him as "younger and stronger." Despite being positive, they plan to continue rehearsing with the singer in January before making a decision.<ref>{{Cite news | last =  | first =  | title = MATT SORUM Says VELVET REVOLVER Is 'Real Close' To Finding New Singer | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = December 17, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=151096}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Zeroing In On 'Younger And Stronger' New Singer | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = December 20, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=151192}}</ref> In January 2011, it was revealed that the band had nine demos recorded, and was due to make a decision on their singer;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.planetrock.com/Article.asp?id=2074676&spid=35830 |title=Velvet Revolver Have Nine Demos Recorded |publisher=[[Planet Rock]] |date=January 10, 2011 |accessdate=January 13, 2011 }}</ref> Matt Sorum also revealed that the band was likely to release its next album before the end of 2011, so long as they find time to record together.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.planetrock.com/Article.asp?id=2077865&spid=35830 |title=New Velvet Revolver This Year |publisher=[[Planet Rock]] |date=January 13, 2011 |accessdate=January 13, 2011 }}</ref> In a video interview with ''Vintage Rock'' at [[NAMM Show|NAMM]] 2011, Sorum stated that the rest of the band do not necessarily share his opinion of the "mystery singer."<ref>{{Cite news | last =  | first =  | title = MATT SORUM Talks To VINTAGE ROCK About VELVET REVOLVER Singer Search (Video) | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = January 20, 2011 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=152549}}</ref> Previous auditionee [[Corey Taylor]] has been rumored to be the singer Velvet Revolver were working with.<ref name="Corey Taylor">{{Cite news | last = Graff | first = Gary | title = Stone Sour's Corey Taylor Addresses Velvet Revolver Rumors, Slipknot's Future | work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date = January 28, 2011 | url = http://www.billboard.com/news/stone-sour-s-corey-taylor-addresses-velvet-1005015472.story#/news/stone-sour-s-corey-taylor-addresses-velvet-1005015472.story}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Taylor neither confirmed nor denied the rumor,<ref name="Corey Taylor"/> while McKagan, in an online chat for [[ESPN]], also stated that he "can neither confirm nor deny" that Taylor was the new singer.<ref>{{Cite news | last =  | first =  | title = Chat with Duff McKagan | publisher = [[ESPN]] | date = February 9, 2011 | url = http://espn.go.com/sportsnation/chat/_/id/36846}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last =  | first =  | title = VELVET REVOLVER Bassist Evasive About STONE SOUR Singer Rumors | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | date = February 10, 2011 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=153713}}</ref> Slash later confirmed that Velvet Revolver were looking at Taylor as a possible replacement for Weiland. However, due to his solo tour, no decision was made.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Devores | first = Courtney | title = Q&A with rock guitar legend Slash | work = [[The Charlotte Observer]] | date = February 16, 2011 | url = http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2011/02/16/2067870/qa-with-rock-guitar-legend-slash.html}}</ref> It has been confirmed that Corey Taylor, vocalist to Slipknot and Stonesour, is now the new vocalist for Velvet Revolver. 

==Musical style==
Velvet Revolver's first album ''[[Contraband (Velvet Revolver album)|Contraband]]'' was described by Johnny Loftus of [[Allmusic]] as an "updated version of Guns N' Roses swagger behind Scott Weiland's glammy, elastic vocals."<ref name="Contraband Review"/> [[David Browne]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' stated that "[a]nyone expecting ''Use Your Illusion III,'' though, will be in for a slight buzzkill" and that "[t]he songs suggest the pop grunge of Weiland's old band more than the careening overdrive of GN'R."<ref name="Contraband ew"/> A number of reviewers made some comparisons to the members previous bands<ref name="Contraband Stylus Magazine">{{cite web | last = Ross | first = R.S. | title = Velvet Revolver - Contraband - Review | publisher = [[Stylus Magazine]] | date = June 30, 2004 | url = http://www.stylusmagazine.com/review.php?ID=2096 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071210002006/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/review.php?ID=2096 |archivedate = December 10, 2007}}</ref><ref name="Contraband Blabbermouth">{{cite web | last = Kaye | first = Don | title = Velvet Revolver - Contraband (RCA) | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | accessdate = November 17, 2010 | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=184}}</ref> with [[PopMatters]] reviewer David Powell stating that "''Contraband'' is a pretty good record of unpretentious rock and roll that suffers from inevitable comparison with the best efforts of its parent bands." He went on to state that while Velvet Revolver's "heritage is evident on most of the songs", ''Contraband'' "improves with repeat listening, which is encouraging."<ref name="Contraband PopMatters">{{cite web | last = Powell | first = David | title = Velvet Revolver: Contraband | publisher = [[Pop Matters]] | date = June 30, 2004 | url = http://popmatters.com/music/reviews/v/velvetrevolver-contraband.shtml}}</ref> With Velvet Revolver's second album ''[[Libertad (Velvet Revolver album)|Libertad]]'' seen the band's style change with the presence of producer [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]], noted by Allmusic reviewer [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]].<ref name="Libertad AMG review"/> Erlewine also stated that "too often, there are concessions between Weiland and the others during the course of a song."<ref name="Libertad AMG review"/> Tom Sinclair of ''Entertainment Weekly'' stated that ''Libertad'' is "feels both comfortingly familiar and vaguely exotic."<ref name="Libertad ew review"/> Songs such as "Let it Roll" and "She Mine" seen some comparisons to [[The Doors]], [[The Rolling Stones]] and [[The Stooges]], noted by ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' reviewer Jaan Uhelszki.<ref name="Libertad SFC review"/> The ''[[New York Post]]'' commented that "Slash's guitar riffs throughout this new record are as aggressive as a caged cat" and "
singer Scott Weiland's vocals are crisp and controlled yet passionate."<ref name="Libertad NYP review"/>

